'''Yuge Shrine''' (ゆげじんじゃ) is a Shinto shrine located in Imazu Town, {{jalink|Takashima City|Q845794}}, {{jalink|Shiga Prefecture|Q131358}}. It is considered to correspond to the “Yuge Shrine” listed in the {{jalink|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932}} under {{jalink|Ōmi Province|Q843882}} {{jalink|Takashima District (Shiga Prefecture)|Q11669692|Takashima District}}, and is regarded as a {{jalink|Shikinaisha}}. However, it lies outside a fence installed to prevent damage by wild animals, making it difficult to visit under normal circumstances.

=== Enshrined deities ===
* {{jalink|Emperor Ōjin|Q317997}}
* {{jalink|Prince Yuge|Q3076827}}
The {{jalink|Tokusen Shinmeichō|Q11571092}} suggests that the deity may be {{jalink|Nigihayahi|Q10949054|Nigihayahi-no-Mikoto}}, the ancestor of Yuge no Sukune.

=== Shrine crest ===
* Left-facing triple tomoe

=== History ===
The date of establishment is unknown, but it is said that when Emperor Ōjin was on his way to {{jalink|Tsuruga City|Q847581|Tsuruga}}, he rested at this place, and the pillow stone used at that time was enshrined as the sacred object. In the 4th year of {{jalink|Kashō|Q1373157}}, the Hachiman deity was enshrined together. In the 9th year of {{jalink|Meiji|Q3125096}}, it was ranked as a village shrine.

=== Festivals ===
* Annual festival: November 3

=== Surroundings ===
* {{jalink|Sakanami-dera|Q11644336}}
* {{jalink|Hioki Shrine (Takashima City)|Q11510250|Hioki Shrine}}
* Umehara Hiyoshi Shrine
* {{jalink|Kumano Shrine (Takashima City)|Q11568963|Kumano Shrine}} (Imazu Town, Inō)
* Imazu General Sports Park

=== Notes ===
