'''Yuge Shrine''' (ゆげじんじゃ) is a Shinto shrine located in Imazu Town, {{ill|lt=Takashima City|Q845794|WD=Q845794|1=Takashima, Shiga}}, {{ill|lt=Shiga Prefecture|Q131358|WD=Q131358|1=Shiga Prefecture}}. It is considered to correspond to the “Yuge Shrine” listed in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} under {{ill|lt=Ōmi Province|Q843882|WD=Q843882|1=Ōmi Province}} {{ill|lt=Takashima District (Shiga Prefecture)|Q11669692|WD=Q11669692|lt=Takashima District|1=Takashima District, Shiga}}, and is regarded as a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}. However, it lies outside a fence installed to prevent damage by wild animals, making it difficult to visit under normal circumstances.

=== Enshrined deities ===
* {{ill|lt=Emperor Ōjin|Q317997|WD=Q317997|1=Emperor Ōjin}}
* {{ill|lt=Prince Yuge|Q3076827|WD=Q3076827|1=Prince Yuge}}
The {{ill|lt=Tokusen Shinmeichō|Q11571092|WD=Q11571092|1=Tokusen Jinmyōchō}} suggests that the deity may be {{ill|lt=Nigihayahi|Q10949054|WD=Q10949054|lt=Nigihayahi-no-Mikoto|1=Nigihayahi}}, the ancestor of Yuge no Sukune.

=== Shrine crest ===
* Left-facing triple tomoe

=== History ===
The date of establishment is unknown, but it is said that when Emperor Ōjin was on his way to {{ill|lt=Tsuruga City|Q847581|WD=Q847581|lt=Tsuruga|1=Tsuruga, Fukui}}, he rested at this place, and the pillow stone used at that time was enshrined as the sacred object. In the 4th year of {{ill|lt=Kashō|Q1373157|WD=Q1373157|1=Kashō}}, the Hachiman deity was enshrined together. In the 9th year of {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}}, it was ranked as a village shrine.

=== Festivals ===
* Annual festival: November 3

